I"‰<p>The internship I have right now just entails me to convert the toolbox theyâ€™ve created in MATLAB to Python. Obviously didnâ€™t know this was going to happen but It definitely has its pros and cons. Con: I spend the entire day reading the documentations of SciPy, MNE, and MATLABâ€™s EEG Lab. Pro: Since I donâ€™t know jack-shit converting someone elseâ€™s badly written code to another language is right up my alley.</p>

<p>The code I had used a Butterworth low-pass filter instead of <a href="https://mne.tools/0.15/auto_tutorials/plot_artifacts_correction_filtering.html#removing-power-line-noise-with-low-pass-filtering">MNEâ€™s inbuilt</a>.</p>

<p>A little bit of research and I guess the first thing you end up on is <a href="https://mne.tools/dev/auto_tutorials/preprocessing/25_background_filtering.html#sphx-glr-auto-tutorials-preprocessing-25-background-filtering-py">this,</a> where oddly enough youâ€™re greeted with a please shoo off this is for math-geniuses only but hereâ€™s the deal:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Filtering is essential, but it can lead to severe distortions if applied incorrectly.</p>

  <p>~ An Introduction to ERP Technique</p>
</blockquote>

<p>In this blog post, weâ€™ll look into custom filters and how we can apply it using MNE.</p>

<p>The problem with using one of MNEâ€™s  inbuilt filters is that the roll-off is actually quite steep and this is quite visible</p>

<figure>
<img alt="before low-pass" src="/images/2021/erp-filters/before.png" height="130%" width="130%" />
<figcaption align="center">Before the low-pass filter</figcaption>
</figure>

